'''Aga Khan''' ({{langx|fa|آقاخان}}, {{langx|ar|آغا خان}}; also transliterated as ''Aqa Khan'' and ''Agha Khan'')<ref name="DaftaryIsmailis2ed">{{Cite book|last1=Daftary|first1=Farhad|author-link1=Farhad Daftary|title=The Ismāʻı̄lı̄s: their history and doctrines|year=2007|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-511-35561-5|edition=2nd}}</ref> is a title held by the [[Imamate in Nizari doctrine|Imām]] of the [[Nizari Isma'ilism|Nizari]] [[Isma'ilism|Ismāʿīli]] [[Shia Islam|Shias]]. From 1957 to 2025, the holder of the title was the 49th Imām, Prince [[Shah]] Karim al-Husseini, [[Aga Khan IV]] (1936–2025). The current holder of the title is the 50th Imām, Prince Rahim Aga Khan, [[Aga Khan V]].

==Title==
The title is made up of the titles "[[Agha (Ottoman Empire)|agha]]" and "[[Khan (title)|khan]]". The Turkish "agha" is "aqa" (Āqā) in [[Persian language|Persian]]. The word "[[agha (title)|agha]]" comes from the [[Old Turkic language|Old Turkic]] and [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]] "aqa", meaning "elder men",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/aga|title=the definition of aga|website=Dictionary.com|access-date=17 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707020835/http://www.dictionary.com/browse/aga|archive-date=7 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=a%25C4%259Fa&x=0&y=0|title=imla|website=www.nisanyansozluk.com|access-date=17 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722111512/http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=a%C4%9Fa&x=0&y=0|archive-date=22 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and means something like "master" or "lord". "[[Khan (title)|Khan]]" means king or ruler in Turkish and Mongolian languages.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Cambridge History of China|last=Fairbank|first=John King|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1978|pages=367}}</ref>

According to [[Farhad Daftary]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iis.ac.uk/view_person.asp?ID=8&type=auth |title=The Institute of Ismaili Studies |url-status=dead |access-date=2 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512113401/http://www.iis.ac.uk/view_person.asp?ID=8&type=auth |archive-date=12 May 2013  }}</ref> a scholar of the Isma'ili movement, ''Aga Khan''<ref>[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]] (2011), [https://books.google.com/books?id=sf9fAwAAQBAJ&dq=Dhani+Pir&pg=PT169 "A Modern History of the Ismailis: Continuity and Change in a Muslim Community", I.B. Tauris & Co., 416 p., pp. 1–2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231194233/https://books.google.fr/books?id=sf9fAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT169&lpg=PT169&dq=Dhani+Pir&source=bl&ots=es8PVBVjUN&sig=AXx4_ZQ55glORlv7FROEWZXCHfk&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjknebX7dbWAhXBJcAKHbXJDKAQ6AEIUjAM#v=onepage&q=Dhani%20Pir&f=false |date=31 December 2018 }} {{ISBN|978-1845117177}}</ref><ref name=Honorific>(...) H.H. the Aga Khan 'who is known amongst his followers by the following names: "''Hazarat Mowlana Dhani Salamat Datar, Pir Salamat, Sarkar Saheb, Huzur Pur Nur, Dhani Salamat, Hazar Imam, Dhani Pir, Aga Khan.''" '</ref> is an honorific title bestowed on [[Aga Khan I|Hasan Ali Shah]] (1804–1881), the 46th Imām of [[Nizari Isma'ilism|Nizari Ismai'lis]] (1817–1881), by [[Qajar dynasty|the Iranian king]] [[Fath-Ali Shah Qajar]].<ref name="DaftaryBib">{{cite book | title=Ismaili Literature: A Bibliography Of Sources And Studies| last=Daftary |first=Farhad |author-link=Farhad Daftary |year=2004| publisher=Institute of Ismaili Studies|isbn=978-1-850-43439-9}}</ref> The Aga Khan III noted in a famous legal proceeding in India that ''Aga Khan'' is not a title but instead an [[Pseudonym|alias]]

